Why is xgboost not calculating the importance for all variables when using it with mlr3?

Short answer: {xgboost} does not return all variables. Longer answer: This is not a mlr3 question but one about the xgboost package. The importance method from this learner simply calls xgboost::xgb.importance . If you look at the example on this page: data(agaricus.train, package='xgboost') bst <- xgboost(data = agaricus.train$data, label = agaricus.train$label, max_depth = 2, (2 more lines were trimmed) This returns > xgb.importance(model = bst) Feature Gain Cover Frequency (4 more lines were trimmed) But there are 127 variables in the total dataset. The maths behind this is just that ranger and xgboost use different importance methods, xgboost only includes the features actually used in the fitted model, whereas ranger uses impurity or permutation and considers all features at all splits. By the way next time please provide a reprex (short reproducible example using easily accessible data and code).
